The Prague stock market went down at the end of the trade
The Prague stock market corrected his losses after the rapid fall this morning.
Transactions in shares in the Czech Energy Enterprise (ČEZ) amounted to nearly half of the usual daily trade.
The Prague stock market continued its fall on Monday from the beginning of Tuesday when it fell by almost six percent.
This time, the fall in Wall Street's shares is behind the decline.
This is how the market's reaction to the vote of the US House of Representatives is manifested, which refused to support the stabilisation plan for the financial sector there.
Shares falling in Asia
The Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall in shares on Tuesday, although some of the losses were finally cancelled during the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng Stock Exchange Index described almost four percent during trading, but later it deleted some of the losses and reduced the decrease to about 2.5 percent.
Hang Seng China Enterprises Index dropped 3.8 percent on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange and the markets in Shanghai were closed.
The stock market in Sydney lost more than five percent, but in the end, losses decreased to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan stock market is down 3.6 percent according to the index there.
"The timing of the American rescue mission is uncertain and affects the world's financial markets," noted Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Finance Council.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines its financial policy independently, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
In Hong Kong, interest rates are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. legislators should resume negotiations immediately and accept the proposal for financial support.
Otherwise, there is a threat that other countries will feel the consequences.
The Bloodbath of American Stocks
On Monday, the U.S. House rejected the draft funding for the financial system, to which 700 billion dollars (almost 12 trillion kroner) should have been spent.
The legislators thus ignored President George Bush's call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the draft would solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilise the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. shares experienced a bloodbath and the leading stock indices recorded the biggest fall in 20 years.
The Dow Jones dropped by almost seven percent, and the last time she experienced a similar fall was 1987.
The index fell before the vote, but as it turned out that the proposal was not adopted in the House of Representatives, the index started to fall free.
Congress withdrew: the US government could pump $700 billion into the banks
The major leaders of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of agreement and financial assistance for the American financial system.
This will be voted on at the beginning of next week.
American legislators have made a breakthrough in the negotiations on the approval of the rescue plan in the form of financial assistance to the US financial system in the amount of $700 billion (about 12 trillion kroner).
But there's no victory yet.
Congress must complete some of the provisions of the agreement before they can make public the final form and vote of the law.
The draft funding for the financial system will be discussed in the House on Monday.
He informed Reuters news agency on Sunday, Barney Frank, president of the Financial Organizations Committee.
According to Senate sources, the draft is likely to be voted on Wednesday as soon as possible.
According to economists, there should be an announcement that the rescue plan will be approved, which is the first important psychological factor in the revitalisation of the financial markets.
However, due to the complexity of the mechanisms, "easing" will then take place.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We've taken a big step.
We have resolved our disparate views on what the form of the market stabilisation package should be like," said the Bloomberg agency, the Democratic Nancy Pelosi.
He said that the final vote could take place on Sunday.
The legislator's representatives met Henry Paulson, the American Finance Minister, on Saturday night to give government funds a permanent form.
This should buy from financial companies the unsellable mortgages that will put financial firms in serious losses and endanger the stability of the whole system.
"We are close to a final agreement on a draft that will work and which must also be effective on the market.
The reform plan still needs to be continued, but I think we're there," said Paulson.
A Signal for Asian Trading
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Senator Harry Reid of Nevada, the legislators are therefore striving to reach a final agreement in Congress on Sunday.
In fact, they want to reassure investors before trading in Asian financial markets, where, due to the time zone, Congress's decision could be the first to influence Monday's trading.
However, it is not yet clear when the two chambers of the U.S. Congress will vote on the law, nor will it be clear whether the trial should not be interrupted at the last minute due to a problem.
Legislators hope that the law will be approved in the next few days.
However, the law is still undergoing a number of changes.
The total amount intended to assist the system shall be divided into two parts.
As requested by President George Bush, the first 350 billion dollars should be available as soon as possible.
However, Congress may block the issuance of the remaining amount, which was set at an additional USD 100 billion and then USD 350 billion, if it feels that the programme is not fulfilling its function.
Bush assessed progress in the negotiations
