The first virtual service provider will reach the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced and our service providers offer virtually the same services as their Western European partners.
Nevertheless, there is something missing here - a virtual service provider that imposes a substantial price reduction on classic service providers.
Maybe it won't be for much longer.
On the Mobil.cz website we have often written that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by ČTÚ, which drew attention to the fact that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in other EU countries.
After the European Commission's latest step to regulate roaming charges, this may lead to a controversial situation - text messages sent from abroad to some Czech mobile operators will be cheaper than domestics.
How is it possible that Czech prices are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to fight.
This may sound controversial, since we have three mobile networks and our penetration is above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office, has often said that there is no room for new service providers in the Czech Republic.
It may be true that the classical service provider with its own network may not have much chance (although it would probably be difficult to find a frequency).
But there is another option - the virtual service provider.
It was the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market that brought about significant price reductions, after which classical service providers had to react.
In the meantime, even before big fish like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, there were voices like ours in Britain.
However, it has been demonstrated that such providers have a place and can indeed be successful.
However, for example, we do not have to go too far.
In February this year, we informed you about the start of the Mobilking virtual service provider in Poland.
In less than six months, this service provider managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest service provider there.
In the meantime, Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which is also the owner of U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the possibility of focusing on a much narrower target group.
In order to operate efficiently, you need much less customers than the traditional service provider.
There is no relatively high cost of building, mobile network operation and maintenance.
Virtual service providers in the world thus generally appear at low cost - offering cheap calls and text messages, which are often counterbalanced by less services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers text messages at least 50% cheaper than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move to bet on a target group.
This service provider focuses specifically on men.
"The real men choose the Mobilking service provider - who they like, whom they can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company operating this virtual service provider.
It is difficult to say whether a vision like the one in Poland could work for us.
Miroslav Čepický, spokesperson of Vodafone, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach, on which most virtual service providers are based.
In addition, it has been relatively satisfactory in terms of the supply of services."
Not a chance in the Czech Republic, claims mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobileking.
"We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not seem very hopeful.
Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," said Jana Studničková, spokesperson of the Penta Finance Group in her telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
This has indirectly shown that existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not very sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they try their best to avoid any potential competition.
The GTS Novera Group has not been hiding its interest in the launch of the virtual service provider for some time now, which aims to take another step towards making Telenica O2 a real competitor in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in providing not only fixed, mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
The sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this option with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations," says Pavel Kaidl, spokesperson of the group.
Maybe it's a better time.
Unofficial information suggests that the first virtual service provider will be lucky by the end of the year.
His birth is, however, surrounded by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not think that a full-fledged virtual service provider should have a place on the Czech market.
Unlike other markets, the Czech market is very special.
To date, we have not been invited by a single subject offering a complex and serious project in this area," he mentioned to Mobil.cz about Vlastimil Sršeň, the Press Department of Telefónica 02.
The other operators also refer to the specific situation of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, spokesperson of T-Mobile, exceptionally in agreement with O2, adds: "So far, no viable and bilaterally beneficial business projects have been recorded on which they could be further based."
And he added: "In the T-Mobile network by the end of the year, it is unlikely that any virtual service provider will show up.
At this moment, we should have a specific agreement at our table so that we can think in such a short term."
Vodafone pays more attention to meeting its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual service providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is exactly what we consider to be the most rewarding in terms of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is a partner for building networks shared for fast mobile internet."
Responsible offices - in line with service providers
The procedure of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would lead to an increase in competition, a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in profits.
So why should we make it easier for such a competition to enter?
When it is important for the service providers, they are able to cooperate, the huzavona surrounding the birth of U:fon also bears witness.
ČTÚ is probably under the greatest pressure around the birth of the T-Mobile company's U:phone.
The publicly available information on the website of ČTÚ bears witness to this.
But right now, the U:phone is a good argument as to why we should not allow the virtual service provider to enter.
Martina Kemrová added: "The environment of the competition in the mobile market has recently been affected by the access of the fourth mobile operator to the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another player into the market and its services would be subject to high requirements."
In view of this attitude of mobile operators, however, the complete lack of interest of the Czech regulators is absolutely amazing.
In the meantime, it is not just the attitude of ČTÚ, which unfortunately has no right to interfere in economic competition in the Czech Republic, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
Only the Competition Authority is entitled to do so.
However, the office has a characteristic attitude towards the whole problem.
"The entry of the virtual service provider into the mobile market would be possible only after the contract between the mobile operator and the virtual service provider was concluded on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for traditional service providers," he said, answering our question about Kristián Chlapua, the External Relations Department of the Competition Authority.
A statement thus formulated by the representatives of the service providers would probably not surprise anyone.
However, from an office that should represent the interests of consumers and, above all, ensure that no one abuses their market position, this is more than odd.
Especially if Kristián Chalupa adds: "Outland, where virtual service providers usually operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in the price of mobile phone services."
However, the interests of the ÚOHS are likely not to be affected by the pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the reduction of prices.
In this case, it is indeed shocking that the three mobile operators' reaction shows quite touching harmony.
The question is, is it really just a coincidence, it almost goes without saying.
Just as the exact same petrol prices at the service stations are probably just the works of chance and hard competition.
"The Office has not discovered any signs of anti-competitive proceedings in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
Neither operator has a leading position, i.e. a proportionately greater responsibility for its market activities.
The tools needed to open the mobile market for virtual service providers are probably also missing by the telecommunication regulator," said Chalupa.
The presentation of the market leader situation is one of the many points of debate.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, on the basis of which telecommunications is the only market from the perspective of economic competition.
Of course, no Czech operator in such a market is then in a leading position.
However, some legal experts also offer a different approach - the approval of the network operator is always necessary for the creation of the virtual service provider.
And the mobile operator, relatively logically, has a monopoly on its own network.
So it's necessarily dominant in a particular segment.
But even if we did not accept this argument, it should be a minimum warning for ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting remarkably similarly.
In the meantime, complaints from a range of interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles during negotiations with all service providers.
Turning responsibility to ČTÚ is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which the UOHS removes their hands from the whole case.
We've seen this before in some similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted telecoms law, the extension of ČTÚ's powers in the field of economic competition could not be carried through in the field of telecommunications, although many experts hoped to improve the situation.
The representatives of the UOHS need to know this well, but they probably have different interests.
This works when no one's watching.
In the meantime, the operation of some kind of pseudo-virtual service provider remains undetected, many of which already operate in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own mobile phone service price lists, but which are only partially public.
It's multi-level marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic company client against the provider, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a prominent customer, you will then receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the trading conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar pre-emption.
"If there were cases you were talking about, it would be a breach of contract terms that we would be dealing with and which could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with the company concerned," replied Martina Kemrová.
But it is highly unlikely that news of this kind of activity would not reach the responsible people of mobile operators.
In particular, the three companies mentioned may have thousands of customers.
Meanwhile, no service provider defends against such proceedings.
In fact, they have a considerable profit from the activities of these companies and, unlike real virtual service providers, they are not particularly threatened by their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of possible problems: "The law allows similar speculation, however, only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card is not in their name on their phone, so they cannot fully have it as general customers of mobile operators."
But that's exactly what ČTú should be saying.
In addition, another question arises for the UOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to a similar procedure, why do they impede the birth of the virtual service provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has a relatively strong power to expose such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the service providers that they did not suspect anything of this kind and that their trading conditions prohibit this.
When we're not the most expensive
As has been said a few times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has led to a noticeable reduction in the price of services.
Meanwhile, in virtually all countries where virtual service providers were established, classical service providers tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, perhaps too satisfied market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, regulatory bodies intervened precisely at these moments, which did not in any way protect the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Then, even through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual service provider to be followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are giving each other the whole case.
From our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclear competences are useful to them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider is really coming out soon, the Czech mobile market may start to move again.
If a provider would allow the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it is difficult for ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may not be making more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to four versions of the new Czech state anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the State Anthem Where Is My Country on the day of the Czech State.
The anthem was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the leadership of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - male or female solos, choir or instrumental.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka sing.
The authors of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on iHNed.cz.
Bělohlavek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful anthems.
He has already told the Czech Radio that he deliberately selected young representative singers to sing solo variations, which are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning, both of them, and later also the orchestra, I tried to ensure that the text was clear and consistent," he said.
The Czech state anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where Is My Country? was first performed in 1834 by Josef Kajetán Tyl Fidlovačka, with František Škroup's music.
It became popular, and people spontaneously viewed it as their own.
The first verse of the song became a natural part of the state anthem after the formation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
Even after the creation of the autonomous Czech Republic, it remained one of the seven State emblems.
