Prague transport company delivers chip cards for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 enters itself in Prague Transport Company's history on the date when the first passenger to board subways, trams and buses will have an electronic coupon in his pocket instead of a paper ticket.
The coupon is currently available to about 100,000 people who have the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day and 90-day and annual coupon (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time save it on chip cards in the information centres and offices of the Transport Company at the Muzeum, M
From yesterday, coupons can be purchased via the Internet via the Website of Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than 400 customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who start using online trading can permanently forget the public windows of metro stations, where they have had to regularly stand long lines for their tickets.
The coupon can be purchased via the Internet and the Opencard card is saved in one of the thirteen branches of the City Library.
"In these places, passengers have a counter with trained servers to help interested parties purchase online and save their coupons for their cards," said Martin Opatrný, spokesperson of the project.
In addition to libraries, electronic coupons can be saved on Opencard in self-service vending machines equipped in some lobbys.
What do these vending machines look like?
Reds, reminding us of ticket managers and the passengers may have already noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, I.P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
"There are currently five of them in town, but there should be 80 by the end of the year," added Opatrný.
The coupon is checked automatically instead of the driver
Their operation tomorrow is easy to handle at start-up machines.
Just insert the Opencard chip card and the previously paid coupon will be saved on its own.
From tomorrow electronic coupons will be valid not only in the capital but also in the surrounding area.
So on the trains and bus lines around the city, from 300 to 499, with which the residents of the districts of central Chechnya travel primarily to the capital city.
"On trains classified as integrated transport in Prague, guides were provided with card scanners to determine the area validity of coupons," explained Philip Dráp, who compiled the schedule for Prague public transport.
In buses around the city, card readers are installed at the cash register at the driver's office.
When boarding, the driver must not only show the chip card, but also place the Opencard in the spot specified on the side of the checkout.
That's how the driver checks the validity of the coupons.
"For example, if the passenger needs to check the validity of the coupons, the easiest way to ask the driver to do so is by adding Drápa."
Passengers who do not travel by buses around the city and will not remember when their coupon expires can go to self-service vending machines that save coupons for cards again.
Information on the validity of their documents is displayed here on the display of the device.
The Sudetes wanted a referendum from the US.
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans requested the attachment of Šumava to the United States.
This can be seen from the letter in the collection of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we can't be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronate of the United States of America.
This is supposed to be the wish that some groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the President of the United States in 1945.
This is also apparent from a letter from a private archive, which is now kept in the collection of the South Bohemian Science Library.
The Germans of Česky Krumlov in the letter ask the US President not to allow the return of the "Sumava county" to the Czech Republic, which was occupied by Hitler under the Munich Treaty.
"The situation has been interpreted correctly and we really want to be sure of the words that the American troops are not coming to German territories as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," it says in the letter, "People who have the fate of Šumava in their hearts".
Since attaching to Czechoslovakia to the Sudeten Germans is supposed to give hope only to brutality, ruthlessness, not understanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the US President to take over Šumava "now and forever".
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of four million inhabitants, this area would be condemned to us as a foreign country that oppresses and destroys the minority, and would not contribute almost anything to the victory of the Allies," states the letter.
The reason the authors couldn't sign it is said to be a fear of revenge from the "cheese oppressors".
