A rat or a moth escapes in the event of danger, does that mean that he feels fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that animals also have feelings.
How, though, can we examine whether they feel the same way when they act like us?
For years, famous scientists have published their articles in the Internet magazine "Edge".
SPIEGEL ONLINE in a series of answers to the question, "What do you think is real without proving it?"
I believe that animals have emotions and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it. It is true that we can’t even prove that other people are conscious.
In this case, however, we can at least hope that the basic configuration of each human brain is the same.
However, as we examine other species and dissect the questions of perception or consciousness in general, we arrive in difficult terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: Pretending to be dead, running or attacking.
Humans behave in a similar way, from which some researchers conclude comparable subjective experiences.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our own subjective experiences to animals.
On the one hand, human consciousness-related circuits almost always contain the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its role in short-term memory and enforcement/control functions).
This broad area is more advanced for humans than for other primates, and it seems to be completely absent for other organisms.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, such as knowing who we are or, in the case of planning and decision-making ability, it is reasonable to assume that man is even different from other primates.
Another dramatic feature lies in the language nature of man: Since a significant part of human experience is related to language, it is often claimed that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, the animals may be excluded.
However, even if it were not dependent on language, it would certainly be influenced by language, so animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
It is therefore difficult to determine what consciousness can be in the case of other animals.
If consciousness cannot be measured either as an internal and subjective thing, and because of special hardware it cannot be analysed on the basis of our own experience, then our research presents us with serious problems.
Most of my ideas relate to the content of conscious living, but there is also another aspect of consciousness, which is probably more accessible to science.
The consciousness processes of animals could be examined regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in short-term attempts at the memory of primates, especially in visualization.
However, this assumption, also examined by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, relies more on the neural connections of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both can be identical or not.
Interestingly, this assumption also emphasizes the importance of prefrontal cortex in visualization.
What does that mean about feelings?
I'm leading this back to the fact that an emotional system, like fear, is activated in a brain aware of its own activity.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state in which we are when the activity of a protective system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupys a memory of work.
In this way, emotions are closely linked to those areas of the cerebral cortex that are typical of primates, and especially humans.
In addition to language, perception is divided into fine degrees, because with words and grammar we are able to distinguish and categorize states to describe them to others as well.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that emotions stem from the simpler activities of cortex and brain stem body perceptions, as well as Jaak Pankseep, who is more focused on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much during human evolution, it can easily play a role in the overarching emotions of the species.
I can't, in theory, deny that, but I find it inconceivable.
Pankseep believes that what appears to be fear in rats and humans in both cases probably also feels like: How can it be checked that rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
A cockroach escapes in the event of danger, does he feel fear?
In my opinion, only similar behavior is not proof of the same experience.
Although neural contusion continues to help: rats and humans have the same brain stem, cockroaches have no brains.
But is the brain stem responsible for the emotions?
And even if this could be proven for humans: how can we prove this in the case of rats?
I think rats and other mammals, but even cockroaches (who knows?) have feelings.
However, I do not know how to prove this.
And since their emotions are suspected to be fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore the emotional behavior of rats rather than emotional emotions.
In any case, progress in this area is expected at the neural level, if measured in rats and humans.
Like rats, I don't research language and consciousness, and I don't study emotion, because I don't know if they exist.
This may seem like a shortsighted approach to others, but I'd rather go ahead than keep hitting the wall.
