Rested Gebrselassie breaks his own world record
The Ethiopian Haile Gebrselassie once again showed why many view him as the best mid- and long-distance runner ever lived when he broke his own world record on Sunday in Berlin, making him the first to run the 42.2 km in 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With the comfortably flat track victory in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie improved 27 seconds on her previous result at 2:04:26, which she achieved last year in Berlin.
By the age of 35, Gebrselassie set a 26th world record of her career in such a wide range of areas that from 1500 metres to the marathon, she had won World Championships in almost every direction or reached a world record.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Olympic marathon in Beijing, fearing - perhaps in retrospect - that air pollution would further aggravate her asthmatic problems.
Instead, he entered the Berlin marathon.
In almost perfect conditions - at sunny time, initially at 9 °C and end at 13 °C - Gebrselassie won on Sunday, at an incredible speed of 2 minutes and 56 seconds per kilometre.
Since the previous marathon runners such as Gebrselassie and the Kenyan Paul Tergat turned to the longer distances, the marathon record has dropped by more than two minutes in the last decade, since the Brazilian Ronaldo da Costa won in Berlin with a 2:06:05 result in 1998.
After the Sunday victory, Gebrselassie told the reporters that two weeks ago, her two calves had a cramp and couldn't train for two weeks.
Clearly, during the forced rest, he was refreshed and not rusty.
"I'm so glad," said Gebrselassie to the reporters.
"Everything worked out perfectly.
I started training again a week ago, and today I had my doubts, but in the end everything was fine."
He received some criticism - especially from Kenya, Ethiopia's Eastern African rival - that he uses too many tools during his competitions, usually avoids many world-famous marathon runners, relies on his pacers as if he were running on track and puts world records ahead of the competitive spirit.
However, this criticism hardly reduces Gebrselassie's greatness in the long run.
Gebrselassie reached the midpoint in 1:02:04 with four Kenyan speed runners on Sunday.
Two high-end Kenyan runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, gave Gebrselassie the rhythm after the runners got tired.
Not much more than 4.8 kilometers ahead of target, Gebrselassie left Kwambai with one last sprint, who finished second with 2:05:36, repairing his individual best by 5 minutes.
Kamathi came in third in 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Irina Mikitenko, born in Kazakhstan, who is now a German citizen, has completed a remarkable year with her seventh fastest victory of 2:19:19.
The world record is held by the British Paula Radcliffe with a time of 2:15:25.
Last spring, 36 - year - old Mikitenko won a surprise at the London marathon with a result of 2:24:14.
He could not participate because of his alleged back injury at the Beijing Olympics, but he quickly recovered and won the Berlin marathon, where he repaired his individual peak by five minutes. This was the third marathon long-distance run he took part in.
He won the race with a clever calculation: first he allowed a group of four Ethiopians and Kenyans to advance and gain significant leadership, then after about 30 km of running after them.
The Ethiopian Askale Tafa Magarsa finished second in 2:21.31, while the Kenyan Helena Kiprop finished third in 2:25:01.
A separate city, the pride and ordeal of black people
In the experience park in Greater Orlando - a few miles from everything that shines, loud and powerful - a quiet small town hides, where the pride and complications of the African-American life experience were born.
Eatonville, the first purely black city that was integrated into the country and which was the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as he described in 1935: "the five lakes, three croquet courses, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, a lot of guavas and two schools without prison."
It's a pilgrimage place now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have attended the annual Zora Festival, which is held in the honor of Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet, in many ways, the town he described and made a tourist attraction, which is also included in the Florida guidebook published by the Project of Federal Writers of the Crisis Age, is separate from his surroundings.
It was as independent, dignified and closed as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that urban blacks in Florida often refused to share their real thoughts with white people, who "know so little about us that they don't know what they're missing."
Even in the year when the black presidential candidate Barack Obama encourages an open discussion on the race issue, many here are distrustful of the looks of outsiders.
"We are very careful how our story is told," reported 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here all his life and is a member of the oldest church in the city.
"You have to say it right."
Eatonville has long been characterized by a paradox of victory and struggle.
At the same time, it is a historic model of black standing, but it is a community of almost 2,400 people, where poverty indicators reach twice the national average.
Partly a literary node, and partly an example of the sometimes looked down, sometimes praised, southern, urban, black culture that flourishes in the shadow of oak trees.
It is not surprising, then, that the residents here are both proud and defensive.
And the picture of Eatonville has been important since Zora (everyone here calls Hurston).
In the books written in the sincere, strong dialect - such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937) - he presented his hometown to the world.
Five sections of the Florida guidebook have transformed the city, which is located near Route 17. This road leads from Florida’s long forgotten center to one of the sites of black history and human drama.
Hurston, who was brave in both life and literature, like drum roll, introduced his readers to the first mayor of Eatonville, Joe Clarke, and then looked into more intimate spheres.
He wrote: "To the right of the road we find the modern public school, brown with white trim, carefully maintained courtyards and playgrounds, which Howard Miller can barely read and write."
He mentioned the widow Dash's new husband, and he wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and anything that might be needed in temporary accommodations."
So Hurston linked Eatonville to autonomy in a few hundred words, but also to illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Clearly, the Fodor's guidebook presented it differently.
Indeed, this description did not please everyone.
"Zora said things the way they were," reported the 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls, who were immortalized by Hurston by quoting the sleazy songs that men sang about their beauty.
He added, "Some people didn't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as the living freak who often visited home after his family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
77 - year - old Augustus Franklin recalled that when Hurston stormed into the city, he usually arrived unannounced in a thundering Chevrolet, smoking cigarettes, and trousers in a city where people are still proud of their dignified dress.
Most people were charmed, Franklin said, but a lot of people paid attention.
"People were always happy to see Zora," said Franklin.
However, on the terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, swinging in his chair, he added: "He never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor, and his books were no longer published.
It seemed that, along with most of the world, Eatonville had forgotten about it.
Although he was once a popular writer, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where he lived.
In Eatonville, there were no major memorials or big public readings.
"I don't think they understood how much he's enriched the world or what he's left us," said Valerie Boyd, author of the Hurston biography published in 2003, "In the Rainbow".
The turning point came in 1980.
Orange County officials wanted to build a five-track road through the city instead of the two-track main street, Kennedy Avenue, which played an important role in the community's life.
The expanding Orlando has already penetrated the Interstate 4 motorways connecting the states on the western border of the city.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering after a difficult period of history.
Among other things, forced integration has put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the battles of racial mixing gave the community a taste of hatred.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys came over and threw oranges and other things at the side of the road," said Franklin.
"There was a lady who died of this.
They threw a watermelon out of a car."
In a letter to The Orlando Sentinel in 1955, Hurston questioned the decision of the Supreme Court requiring violent integration, saying of the resolution "Brown v. Board of Education": "It offends rather than respects my race."
Today, residents say that although the desegregation of schools was positive in some respects, it weakened the cohesion of the Eatonville people and undermined the confidence of young people.
"Black children are used to being hugged - I remember this - by hugging their teachers both in the morning and in the evening," reported N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins, managing director of the nonprofit organization "Let's Keep Meg Eatonville Community".
"This lasted until the students and teachers came from a common place," he added.
"We didn't hug our white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean, there were cultural differences between us," said Nathiri.
However, human rights have helped the rise of many other Zora Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists who have surpassed prejudices, as he has done, with such positive self-confidence and lines as: "How can anyone deprive himself of the pleasure of my company!
This is beyond my understanding."
In 1975, Alice Walker wandered off to Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight to restore her reputation.
Five years later, on the shelves of bookstores, Robert E. Hemenway wrote a renowned biography of Hurston, which once again placed him among America's role models.
The road construction project would have started just as the most famous daughter of Eatonville was refocused.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw him as a savior.
The community started organizing a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the county would ruin with its main road.
Thousands of fans arrived at the opening event two years later, and since then many have returned to the ceremony every January.
Several years later, the county stopped proposing road construction.
"Due to the five lanes of the main road, the community was revived, turned to full speed, which means true civic pride," said Nathiri.
Boyd put it easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the road construction project helped to change the city's self-conceived image.
More and more people from outside the city appeared, such as lawyer Rachelle Munson, who began to attend church here in 1993, and the locals began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the national historical list in 1998.
In 2006, the new one-story library (of course named after Hurston) was opened, on rehubbed and beautiful Kennedy Avenue.
Eatonville remains the cuckoo egg of Florida: it is not only 10 km from the centre of Orlando, but sometimes it feels like a suburban side street during summer rain; it is as small as when 27 black families founded it in the 1880s.
(Today 90% of the inhabitants are black.)
They still take care of outsiders who come here looking for something to say, the story of Eatonville.
Most interviews require prior permission, and some things - such as the oldest fresco in Eatonville, depicted by a white man who painted and works in the fields - should not be photographed.
Many people in Eatonville, including the confident teacher Jones, who is particularly attracted to bright red, fear that their separate communities are misunderstood.
And yet, as the Hurston Festival grew wider, the pride of the hometown grew.
In particular, young people increasingly view Eatonville as Hurston saw his own species: wonderful, troublesome, or worse, just as proud, creative, diligent, foolish and confused as other racial and ethnic groups in America.
There is a genuine civil attachment in the words of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return after graduating from college to work with the local government or the police, who he believes needs help.
And it seems the younger ones have learned to describe Eatonville correctly, such as the 11-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alexia Kenon.
"Most people who travel through here think this town is nothing compared to the rest," said Alondra Kenon recently after the service on Sunday.
"But if someone stops and takes some time to get to know their history, it's a very nice city."
We all speak the language of finance here in New York.
Nothing on the surface has changed.
If tourists didn't care about the newsstand booths and the huge television projectors in Times Square, they wouldn't notice they were in the middle of a storm.
They would never realize that with the glass-walled beehive-shaped offices above their heads, bankers and venture fund managers, who hold New York in their power, have been living the hardest days since 1929.
The couriers are still knocking their metal tea trucks down the sidewalks, delivering muffin trays for morning meetings.
Men with Spanish lips still shuffle around the blocks, carrying 50 ironed shirts as human mules, hanging from a yokelike loop across their shoulders.
The office staff are still waiting in line for their sweet breakfast pastries on the sidewalk for food trucks, and it is still impossible to catch a taxi between 4 and 7 p.m. on weekdays.
I didn't feel like there was any crisis until Thursday afternoon, despite all the ominous news, I decided to open a new bank account.
Although I purposely planned to take care of it during the afternoon’s quiet in the local branch of my JP Morgan Chase bank, I had 20 people in line for me.
Not at the bank teller's window, where you can withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service desk, where older customers order a checkbook, tourists ask for directions to Macy's store, and where new customers open a bank account.
Many before me - I learned later from Starr, the "ordered" banker - stood in line with the same intent as me.
However, unlike me, they have already taken their money out of smaller banks in their homes, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They took money out of so-called savings banks (such as housing cooperatives), credit unions and small-town savings banks operating in only one state and allegedly treating their customers as family members.
In the last year, 15 of these banks have gone down quietly.
In the last few days, Washington Mutual, a bank with a capital of $327 billion, has been in bankruptcy, and when New Yorkers left on Friday night for the weekend, another bank, Wachovia, made a savings of $440 billion to save a bank saver.
The office and shop workers before me, fearing another collapse, moved their money to a bank that seemed to be a safe haven for the bank that was buying out most of the capital injections on Wall Street.
The simple people of New York have become experts in finance over the past few weeks.
A woman at the local Chinese store on her phone spoke of the bankrupt Lehman Brothers bank and its huge-looking CEO, Dick Fuld, as if she were complaining about a lazy colleague.
Lyn, the janitor of my apartment block in uniform, in his 50s, changed the subject, and we're not talking about Brad and Angelina or my food shipment, like we used to.
He said to me after I went to the bank, "I invested all my savings in money market assets.
I've changed, I'm not taking any chances."
