"I don't take pictures on stage because I want to introduce the artist from a personal side" Photographer Günther Bauer
No set, no ruffles, no dancing shoes.
The great masters of flamenco are close by, without the excitement of the performance: to get to know the everyday faces of the dancers.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the ordinary man.
And these two sides cannot be separated, except in intimate moments far away from the audience, when we can watch a personal movement, grasp the depth of a captured look, or marvel at the beauty of the idle but expressive hand of an artist not about to perform on stage.
In the German Günther Bauer Flamenco-people photo series, he combines the theatricality of singers, dancers and guitarists with this less-known everyday side of the masters.
Through the photos, the unique iconography of flamenco is presented from different angles.
The exhibition, which is part of Flamenco Photography Month, "reflects the increasing international importance of flamenco every day," the creator believes, adding that Flamenco-people could be a "actor" of anyone, since in view of the images, the observer realizes that these images do not represent artists in a typical way.
These people on the street are artists who are able to bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and enslave the audience.
On the other hand, stage photography is not suitable to capture their personality.
Their personality and character reside in the depths of their beings.
I wanted to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture the personality of the greats of flamenco with the help of the camera."
The Cante de las Minas festival gave Bauer the impetus to his long journey in 1997, where he made portraits of flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers with a record camera.
Thanks to the camera and the choice of subjects, these portraits quote classical photography.
However, the application of various stylistic tools breaks off with traditional visual representations and suggests modernity. The following idea faithfully reflects Bauer's idea of flamenco: "This is a music with traditional roots, which changes day by day and is always fascinating."
It's not the dance itself, it's not the music itself, it's the artist's personality and character that charms the audience.
Recently, the leading motif of the works seen in the El Fotómata gallery is the search for an encounter with the essentials, the artistic sewing, which becomes visible through the way of perception, existence and visualization.
Known figures of flamenco, including Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Moreente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, are hallmarks of this collection of photographs presenting almost 60 artists.
The project also became flamenco anthology, which will soon be published with an album covering the portraits presented at the exhibition.
Bauer's passion for portraits inspired him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "PortARTproject" series "PortARTprojects of Veteran athletes".
Although Flamenco-people has a slightly different concept, the photographer adds: "I really like to photograph people, get to know them and enter their lives for a longer or shorter moment.
In my opinion, the most difficult genre of photography is the portrait.
You meet people, you meet people, you meet people you don't even know sometimes, or you just take a few minutes to shoot.
But despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas.
A selection of contemporary flamenco portraits, entitled Flamenco-people, can be seen in El Fotómata Gallery at the Kalle de la Mata 20 in parallel with Alameda de Hércules until October 16th.
