After three drunk-driving offences, the Ministry of Interior would require the driver to install a device that would prevent the vehicle from being launched if the driver was drunk or not blowing into the structure.
The proposal was presented in June and is currently being dealt with by the State's Attorney's Office, according to which the pilot project will last for a year.
Since the aim of the project is to return to the market, the driver will also have to take a repeat course on transport education.
In addition to the Public Prosecutor’s Office for Transport, DGT and the Foundation for Auto Safety Technology (FITSA) participate in the experiment.
According to the statistics, 30-75% of motorists arrested several times for drunk driving are back in the car.
This would be prevented by Alcolock, since the system connected to the vehicle determines the alcohol level of the air sprayed in it. If it is greater than the permitted or if the driver has not blown into the device at all, the system will not allow the car to start.
The cost of the instrument of more than EUR 1000 would be borne by the infringer.
A relevant study in the USA in 2007 demonstrated that vehicles equipped with such instruments could reduce the number of infringements by up to 65% in the first year after installation.
In Spain, it is estimated that this rule could save 115 lives a year.
The measure focuses on infringements for two reasons: on the one hand, it is easier to prevent them from turning into criminal offences;
on the other hand, it is easier to introduce, since the implementation of the legal reform is in the normal course of action, whereas the necessary reform in criminal matters would require an amendment of the basic law.
The instrument is not yet commercially available on the Spanish market, although it has already been installed in experimental mode in some industrial and public vehicles.
The House will vote tomorrow on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party which, on a French sample, calls for the system to be installed in school buses.
