Blood Safe Again
Dr. Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate, because Héma-Quebec has become one of the safest and most effective blood donors in the world today.
Most importantly, he managed to regain the trust of people, which was severely shaken by the scandal of infected blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As it is known, the national blood reserve managed by the Red Cross blood supply in Canada was infected with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and the general upheaval, the Government of Canada launched an official investigation in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, which was intended to shed light on the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to make proposals to avoid similar cases in the future.
While Judge Krever has delayed his report, some provinces have set up their own committees to design a new blood management system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee had this task.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two blood supply services were established in Canada: one is Hema-Québec, the other is Héma-Québec, the other is the Canadian Blood Supply Company, responsible for all the provinces and the two territories.
"When Héma-Québec began its activities in 1998, only 38% of the people had confidence in Quebec's blood supply system," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was desperate.
"In the coming years, however, as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the field, we have managed to regain the trust of people." Décary proudly states that by the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population considered Héma-Québece to be reliable.
However, Dr. Décary does not forget that "trust is extremely fragile".
Since the foundation of Héma-Québec on 28 September 1998, the principle of caution has been applied.
During this period, many cases of mad cow disease, the new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were discovered in Europe, says the doctor, who has been in charge of the company since its foundation in 1998.
"We had no idea that this disease was spreading through blood.
Therefore, we have been relying on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports. According to this, if we are uncertain about this and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, we must apply exclusion measures. In this case, it was Creutzfeldt-Jakob’s disease, which causes brain changes, which inevitably leads to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not accept blood from persons who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
And a few years ago, there was no doubt that the disease spreads through blood.
This case convinced us that we had reason to apply the principle of caution."
In 1999, a technique appeared on the market that allows a more sensitive diagnosis of HIV virus. This nucleic acid test (NAT), which is able to detect the virus directly in the blood of blood donors, rather than antibodies against the virus on which the tests used earlier were built.
Using the NAT test, we were able to shorten the window period, which takes as long as we can detect the virus in the blood using our technical tools, explains the expert.
This period could be reduced for a period of less than one week.
Thus, they significantly mitigated the risk of unknowingly infecting blood cells by blood donors, and that this could not be detected.
These developments have greatly reduced the risk of spreading AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of getting HIV-infected blood is 12 million to one.
"In other words, this means that we should distribute 12 million blood products while someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 and 500 thousand blood products each year, it would take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and someone to become infected with HIV via a blood product.
I think that anyone can now accept or prescribe blood transfusions in order to restore health, says the number one leader of Hema-Québec.
"The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what new pathogen will enter the system.
After all, it was only last year that the chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, enters the blood with insect bites.
Therefore, we need to keep an eye on it," Dr. Décary continued, and stressed that in addition to emergency reserves, Héma-Québec should provide sufficient permanent reserves.
"The ageing of the population also increases the demand.
Since anticancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects blood donors, as the number of people in the network capable of donating blood accounts for only 3% of the Quebec population.
However, every healthy person at least 18 years of age who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of applicants do not accept blood because they are infected with AIDS or malaria, and those who have been in countries where malaria kills are not eligible for blood donation for a year.
"With this 3 percent, we have enough reserves to meet the needs of hospitals.
It's very rare to run out of supplies.
However, we need to increase the number of blood donors to the extent that existing ones are getting older, because they can't give blood after a while.
However, it is very difficult to convince people to donate blood, but it is even more difficult to keep them and get them to become regular blood donors.
In today's rushing world, man barely has a single hour to go and donate blood," regrets Francine Décary.
Héma-Québec, an annual budget of USD 297 million, provides not only blood products but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin tissue, which is used almost exclusively for severely burned persons.
These tissues are analyzed, modified and frozen, and then placed at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public stem cell bank in Quebec.
Only a cord that has been treated as medical waste can be extracted from blood that is rich in stem cells, including severe diseases (such as leukaemia).
"Some weeks ago, we celebrated the entry of the thousandth cord blood sample into our bank, and we plan to take over a thousand new samples each year.
At the beginning of next year, we will probably start offering them for organ transplants," said Dr. Décary, who said that the cord blood removal program is very popular today.
"Many mothers are sad that they do not have the opportunity to do so" - indeed, because Héma-Québec is not able to make this complex and costly program available in all Quebec hospitals.
