In the September 17th issue of Le Devoir, a letter was published by Patrick J. Garver, the deputy president and CEO of the Canadian Barrick Gold mine.
Following Orwelli's discussion, Garver states that the world's largest gold company has filed a $6 million defamation suit against three authors and a small-money publishing company in order to initiate a so-called "public debate".
Although the judges are independent and impartial, their decision, especially in defamation cases, is made not on the basis of the truth, but by the law.
Not surprisingly, Garver was deeply silent about this fundamental difference.
For Barrick Gold, would it really be the best way to have a public debate to destroy anyone whose position is contrary to his?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publishers of the book Noir Canada must spend considerable money on defence and struggle in an unequal fight where, on the other hand, there are an army of lawyers supported by almost inexhaustible sources of the mining industry.
In such an unequal struggle, it is often the tactic of destroying the defendant and concluding a friendly agreement that not only silences the opposite, but even intimidates those who try to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, he should have expressed his views to the public.
Although in many other countries where Barrick Gold is active, this is done differently, in Canada, disputers do not usually strike each other with sticks, but express their thoughts.
The mine would therefore have been sufficient to open its books and dossiers and prepare for a real debate in the press, media and publications, paying for independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But it seems that Barrick Gold doesn't trust public opinion and, in a single move, sweeps aside requests and letters written to protect the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how you can initiate a "public" debate if, at the same time, you ignore this public opinion?
In the mind of the vice president, this word probably only means the highly paid lawyers, not the total population of Canada: the meaning of the concept narrows down considerably.
In a democratic state, even those who abuse others deserve freedom of speech.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the authors and publishers of Noir Canada are primarily supported by the public because it condemns the harsh procedure of the mine.
The public is prepared to listen to Barrick and to make a judgment, but this would be done on the basis of civilized arguments rather than by a lawsuit for silence for many. (In relation to the term "public debate", Barrick Gold has recently called on Noir Canada authors to refrain from using this term.)
In addition to the surreal discussions of Garver, Barrick Gold's process is an open attack on the freedom of university research and the search for truth, which are building blocks of all democratic societies.
The procedure as a whole denies the right to quote credible sources and to a debate on the facts and their interpretation, which form the basis for spiritual activities.
If in a country like Canada you can only study and discuss matters that are not pleasing to the rich companies of today’s world, will you take the liberty of doing so?
If Barrick Gold really wants an open and transparent debate, it could do so according to the scientific standards applied by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have the right to respond.
We have been able to handle disputes, disagreements and conflicts in our university community for a long time.
Barrick Gold's unthinkable procedure shows that, contrary to what it claims, it is not in the mood to have an open debate.
This is a loss for both the world of universities and the institution of public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to finally introduce measures that restrict legal procedures for such abuse.
