The psychology of overbiding: why are we giving out more money?
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overvalue goods.
The neuro-economic foundations of this known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been explored by neurologists and economists at the University of New York.
According to a study published in Science magazine, people do not want to lose out on a type of competition, such as eBay’s auction, so they pay an overprice.
He was trying to map this "play" neural pattern of research using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other group took part in a playful auction, while testing the active brain areas of the test subjects using the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) method.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction, in which the overbiding of the other party is an essential element, the subcortical complex called striatum was activated intensively when the game was lost.
This brain space plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system in addition to several other functions.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the upsetting of the price can be explained by avoiding the intense reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theory, financial follow-up was also carried out by the economists of the research group.
In this three groups bid against a partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product and they made their bets.
Another group was also promised that if they were to win, they would be rewarded with $15 more money.
The third group, on the other hand, had just received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a losing auction, members of the group also lost this money.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, only that one of them was stressed to win and the other to lose.
However, by proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the team playing "against loss" were willing to bet higher than both the control and the "winner" groups.
"These results cannot be derived from any pre-existing economic theory.
To date, they have only explained the phenomena of the auction with the joy of winning and avoiding risks.
Only neurological imaging methods helped to resolve the contradiction between these two theories by now reaching a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when should we seek medical attention?
About half a billion people around the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death in Hungary.
Hundreds of thousands of people are infected with hepatitis at home, but only 7,000 are treated, which is why patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is a collective name for infectious liver diseases caused by different viruses.
Their symptoms have many similarities, characterized by inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases are different.
The hepatitis viruses are transmitted in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the gastrointestinal tract (e.g. contaminated food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (intoxication, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travelers should be advised to defend themselves against virus A and B by vaccination, and there is no vaccine against virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after eating the infected food, generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal discomfort and nausea.
Thereafter, jaundice on the skin and whites of the eyes develops, the stools become light, the urine becomes dark, healing may take two to three weeks.
One million people around the world die of more severe types of disease, hepatitis B liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected patients receives medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and cancer of the liver.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease, because the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms are only 20 to 30 years from now.
Thus, early prevention, regular screening, is very important afterwards.
In three groups, this disease is well above average: between people undergoing blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
There are currently 200 million chronic hepatitis C virus infected in the world.
Since the disease may be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is recommended that you contact your family doctor if you experience any symptoms of unknown cause.
In time, recognising the disease can be cured, the virus can be eradicated from the body, thereby eliminating the infectivity and preventing cancer from developing.
September 30th is the World Day for Hepatitis, first organized in 2004 by organisations representing patients around the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to the chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God hurt less?
According to a recent study, religious faith acts as a kind of analgesic that could have facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment, examining how belief in God affects people's sense of pain, reported the British Telegraph.
In a rather bizarre investigation, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were electroshocked while all of them were studying a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to rule out much of the pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was also revealed that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for controlling pain.
The investigation is the first in a series of research in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university participate alongside academics.
The investigation was carried out precisely by attaching a sparkling device to the left hand of the test subject, which provided the electroshock.
Researchers asked participants to look closely at two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and Leonardo da Vinci's Lady Hermeline painted in the 15th century.
The investigators hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would cause a religious state among the believers, while the image of da Vinci was chosen because it was not too different from the other and was thought to be soothing.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, during which they received 20 electroshocks in four successive episodes while either looking at the religious theme or the general picture.
The Catholics reported that they felt "safe" in the sight of the Virgin Mary, like they were "careful" and "rested, filled with peace".
While watching the religious picture, 12 percent less pain was reported than when Leonardo’s creation was seen before.
Miguel Farias, a psychologist who himself participated in the study, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any powerful image, including atheists, only the right photo should be found.
"We should find an image that they feel very positive about, like a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Bishop Tom Wright of England welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should and in many cases changes our personality," said Wright.
After the great results, the question is, if Leonardo or a painter of the same calibre were to show a picture of a madonna to the believers, how would that affect their pain control?
Would the sight of a quality Virgin Mary bring even better results?
