A bumblebee's flight is simulated by an intelligent car
What would be the best way to develop technologies to avoid collision if not to imitate barrier sensors in the world of nature?
Like bees.
In the surprising project presented at the CEATEC in Japan, the bumblebees gave Nissan engineers the strategic idea of how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In cooperation with the Tokyo university, Nissan built the BR23C bio-imitating auto-robot management system, a robotized mini-car that was endowed with bees' properties, with the ultimate aim of facilitating the development of a system that eliminates all collisions.
During the flight, each bee creates its oval-shaped personal space, which is in fact very similar to our safety cover, explained Kazuhhiro Doi, trade director of technology PR and R & D at the exhibition.
The role of the complex eye of the uterus is important, which can see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the complex eye, engineers reached out to the idea of laser telemetry.
This identifies obstacles in a 180-degree field of vision before BR23C, calculates their distance, and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts into an action to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second, the obstacle is detected, then the car robot, imitating the movements of the uterus, changes direction immediately by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to avoid impact.
In a way other than any current system, this avoidance maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive manner.
"If this were not the case, the auto robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Head of Mobility Laboratory and the auto-robot project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety cover, a layer within which the collision is currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process should reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
However, in a way other than bees, the deviation must not be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it must be only two-dimensional, and only towards the rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available for bees to avoid other bees, only rotating movement and acceleration and slowing down were used as the available option for the car robot.
BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have higher energy density, which means they have a longer life span than lithium-ion.
Andoh believes that an instinctive intelligent response is the important, not the ability to process data, even less storage.
This device only has to process and respond to a few input signals per second.
There is no need to preserve them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so they use only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
There is no need for gigabytes or megabytes of memories.
This is the first step towards the development of instant bypass technology, which Nissan estimates will be able to enter mass-produced cars within ten years.
A further possibility of application may be the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to lead the driver to the specified destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
