Moreover, the programme differs from the initial proposal of the Bush Administration, which would have meant that the $700 billion would have been spent one-on-one on the purchase of poor quality credit-backed securities.
Now, in the first round, a maximum of half of the 700 billion can be spent by using 250 billion immediately after Congress is expected to vote on Monday, from which the Ministry of Finance buys loan-backed, bad-rated securities, and the fate of an additional 100 billion dollars depends on the President's decision.
The program will be monitored by a separate body, including the President of the Federal Reserve.
Spending the other half of the 700 billion will depend on a new resolution from Congress.
