The domestic sales prices of the industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month and by 12.9 percent in August 2007, reports KSH.
Industrial export sales prices were 1.1 percent higher compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 percent compared to one year earlier.
As a result of the domestic and export price changes, industrial producer prices were 0.7 percent higher than the previous month and 3.2 percent higher than the previous year.
The domestic sales prices of the industry increased only to a minimum of 0,1 percent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices of the manufacturing sectors also increased slightly by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The highest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), mainly due to a 4.6 per cent increase in the production of bags and straps and a 2.5 per cent increase in the monthly production of footwear.
The higher price levels of plastic and chemical inputs have resulted in a significant monthly increase in prices in the chemical and product manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
Price reductions occurred in the oil processing (1.4 per cent), in the production of electrical machinery and equipment (0.9 per cent) and, to a minimum, in the wood processing (0.1 per cent) sectors.
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
In the other manufacturing sectors, we measured a price increase between 0.2% and 0.9%.
In August, prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector with a significant weight in domestic sales of the industry increased by 0.3 percent, mainly due to the pervasive effect of the regulatory gas price increase from 1 July.
Twelve months in comparison - domestic sales of the manufacturing sectors - the highest increase in prices in the oil processing sector (32.4 percent).
In the metalworking industry, an 11 percent increase in prices was observed in the food, beverage and tobacco production sector, with a dominant weight.
Price reductions occurred in textiles, textile products (2.5 per cent) and electrical machinery and instruments (0.3 per cent) sectors.
In the other manufacturing sectors, the rate of price increase was between 0.6 and 9.1%.
Prices have increased by 10.2 percent in the manufacturing industry as a whole over the last year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors were 18.7% higher than the ones one year earlier.
Domestic sales showed the highest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) in August in the sectors producing capital goods.
In the sectors producing consumer goods, prices have increased by 0.3%, and in the energy and downstream sectors, prices have not changed compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, the highest price increase compared to the same month of the previous year was observed in energy and downstream sectors (16.8 per cent).
In the sectors producing consumer goods, we measured a 6,8 percent increase in prices and a 1.4 percent decrease in prices for capital goods.
Export sales prices of the industry, measured in HUF, increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, and decreased by 3.9 percent in comparison to 12 months.
