The European Equal Opportunities Summit started today in Paris, where France, representing the Presidency-in-Office of the European Union, hosted this year.
Lívia Járóka, Fideszwoman of the European People's Party, addressed education segregation in her message to the plenum as one of the main speakers of the professional conference, because it is one of the most serious violations affecting Roma children and, moreover, the most serious obstacles to their implementation.
The high-level conference, on behalf of the French Presidency, was opened by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Representatives of governments, the European social partners and the most important European rights defenders and civil society organisations in the field of equal opportunities were invited to the meeting.
Járóka, according to the press office of the Fidesz EP Group, warned that, in addition to discrimination in recruitment, Roma are mainly excluded from the labour market because of their low level of education.
"The vast majority of Roma youths have no secondary education, and only a small proportion of them can obtain higher education due to poor quality primary education".
Járóka also stressed that, as a fundamental human right, education has a key role to play in the enforcement of other human rights.
Investing in early education for Roma children could mean strengthening the economy of the EU Member States.
According to the congresswoman, it is necessary to raise awareness of these relationships in the broadest range, including among Roma and non-Roma.
Because the sooner the Roma student starts school, the chances of becoming productive members of the labour market increase; they contribute to the national budget through taxes on income and consumption.
"Romas must have the right to quality education by virtue of their citizenship of the European Union and must be guaranteed the elimination of their low quality and separate education", said Lívia Járóka.
According to the MEP, it is essential to bring together the European Union's goal and action-oriented cooperation in order to speed up the desegregation processes at school immediately, with proper enforcement of existing and planned anti-discrimination directives being essential.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be broken, Roma children must be given the opportunities of democratic space so that they can contribute to Europe's future as full citizens", said Járóka.
In the spirit of the European Year of Equal Opportunities for All, the European Equal Opportunities Summit, which took place annually since last year's meeting in Berlin, aims to provide a unique forum for promoting the objectives of equal opportunities and non-discrimination at European and national level.
