Mp3 players may cause hearing loss
Listening to portable recording devices at longer and high volume, such as MP3 devices, can cause permanent hearing loss -
published in Brussels on the basis of an opinion published today by the European Commission, the EU Scientific Committee on New and Newly Identified Health Risks (SCENIHR).
"It turns out that 5-10 percent of people who listen to their portable music player with a high volume for more than one hour per day for five years can suffer permanent hearing loss," he explains.
"It is worrying that young people who use high volume portable music players and mobile phones in mass and often are not aware that they can irreversibly damage their hearing," said Meglena Kuneva.
"Scientific surveys indicate an undisputed risk, which we urgently need to respond to," added the EU Commissioner.
The most important task is to inform consumers and to disseminate information about them widely.
In the light of this opinion, we also need to review existing control systems so that they can function effectively and keep pace with the latest technologies".
Brussels invited the independent scientific committee to examine the problem in view of the prevalence of portable music players and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise pollution caused by them.
"The researchers confirm that we have cause for concern, and the European Commission, in cooperation with Member States and stakeholders, is ready to examine possible measures to protect children and minors exposed to noise pollution caused by portable players and similar devices," the Committee finally said.
The current European safety standard sets the maximum noise levels for portable music players at 100 dB; however, there is growing concern about hearing loss data resulting from the excessive use of such sound sources.
At the same time, there are solutions, such as reducing the level and duration of noise pollution, which can significantly reduce these hearing loss.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee explains that for people using portable recording devices who listen to music at a high volume (more than 89 decibels) for five hours a week, noise pollution exceeds the current maximum noise at work.
If a person listens to music in similar circumstances for a longer period of time, there is a risk of permanent hearing loss after five years.
This affects about 5-10 percent of people who use portable devices, which could mean 2.5-10 million people in the EU.
