The Elite Is In Danger
The phenomenon was felt a few days ago when the House did not vote for the $700 billion rescue package presented by the White House: a significant part of Americans were more interested and still interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is supported by yesterday's New York Times, which informs us that the current crisis has led to a break in the Republican Party, which is increasingly divisive between the traditional, restrained East Coast attitudes supporting federal institutions and business circles and the ever-increasing new anti-D.C. and financial trends in the Middle and Southern States.
This line was critically manifested in the vote in the House referred to in the introduction.
However, this event is only one of the major changes that the economic restructuring still taking place predicts or permits to be seen, not only in the United States, but also throughout the Western world, perhaps even beyond.
It seems that the crisis, both in the US and in Europe, is speeding up the phenomenon that has been laying low for a long time and which is solidified in this new atmosphere and is finally coming to light.
The first such phenomenon is re-updating, bringing back the dual category of state sovereignty into the public consciousness, in connection with a kind of re-nationalisation of the economy.
The crisis is affecting banking and financial institutions which, although having a close relationship with the rest of the world, are, first and foremost, and quite widely, bringing people and families with them that live in a single country, in a single state.
This, on the other hand, is a direct political problem for those on the government: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people who are also electorate.
So the crisis seems to be global in economic terms, but it is almost exclusively national in political terms.
It seems that political internationalism is essentially stranded outside the coastline: the European Union is an excellent proof of this, which cannot set a single policy stance, inter alia, between different interests and different national strategies.
Thus, everyone expects the intervention, the rescue package, the recovery and the new rules, but above all the opening up of funds: because only individual states have economic resources, a financial set that can make things right.
They also have the means and the authority to use them: in certain circumstances, they have two invaluable sources which no other market or international organisation will likely ever have.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed by the crisis on the nation state is fully in line with the fact that recent economic growth attaches increasing importance to a factor that is closely related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had already entered the abstract world of the network, the increasingly sophisticated technology, and we were convinced that the global financial world was destined to rule the world, we suddenly had to realize that our future depended on things that were increasingly, least not abstract, like water, crop and oil.
Things that can be transported from one side of the planet to another, yet are entirely linked to a demarcated location, an area.
So whoever controls the area has a lot more cards than who, unfortunately, was born in a place where there is no crop, no oil, and no water.
Which brings me to the second novelty, which suggests a kind of fault line.
Anyone who says it's territory, state, government, necessarily says it's politics, in other words, leadership.
From this point of view, the economic crisis seems to be producing two converging phenomena:
On the one hand, the objective recognition of the need for credible leadership, someone who can take control of events.
On the other hand, it brings complete credit losses from current management, especially economic leaders, who have proved to be completely inadequate and have proven that they still have a lot of obscure areas ahead of them.
Together, the two are even more important and, in a sense, more disturbing: a sense of credit loss, impatience, inadequacy and dissociation, affecting the entire leadership elite in more and more Western countries.
It seems, therefore, that the belief that the time of the highest social elite has passed has spread among the wider population. It expired before their actions, experiences, lifestyles, cultures, in the complex sense of the word, became their own. This makes the social elite increasingly alienated from the majority’s opinions.
In short, the need for leadership, in a veiled form, feeds a diverse but strong delegitimation movement against the ruling class and the traditional political system. This is not expected in the "rebellions" of the voters, or in recent times in the sudden changes of the public mood. For example, the rise of conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of the Labour Party Unit in Great Britain, or the rebellion of American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the Italian right side).
It seems that the traditional elite, along with their parties, programs, and even their customs, press and renowned intellectuals, are becoming less and less understood and therefore less able to represent what has been going on for some time in the deeper parts of Western society. Furthermore, the economic crisis is intensifying, spreading and potentially able to generate an ever greater degree of anger.
Nevertheless, speaking of "the imminent rebellion of the masses" is, frankly, an exaggeration.
