Traditional cinemas close for Multiplexes.
"A city with no movies, a blind city, like a face without eyes."
The pictures taken by the director Giuseppe Tornatore show effectively what is happening in Italian cities, but also in rural regions.
Extinguishing cinemas - the appearance of large, multi-term cinemas in the suburbs, and consequently the decay of single-term cinemas in the city centres - is an inevitable and irreversible process, but at the same time bears all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
When historical and memorable places disappear, "it's like a friend leaving, a friend with whom we shared our journey and many experiences," says the director of Cinema Paradiso. Twenty years ago, the film, which represented the Oscar Award and the Grand Prize of the Cannes Festival, tells the lyrical story of a small-town cinema, the longing after a movie experience that may have been lost forever.
The data provided by Anec, the largest association of operators, is clear: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed down. The biggest losses were recorded by cinemas in large cities: 10 cinemas closed in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Emilia-Romagna is at the forefront of the most affected regions, which lost 82 single-room cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And that the expansion of multiplexes is precisely the same as the highest number of newly opened multi-room cinemas in these three regions of Italy: in the last five years, the number of halls has increased by 195 in Lombardy, 81 in Tuscany and the same amount in Emilia-Romagna.
"The number of units in Italy has increased irrationally," says the President of Anec Paolo Protti. "It is okay to build new facilities, but the survival of the already existing ones should also be ensured, because when a city cinema closes, not all the goers are willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention uncharged financial funds to support operators: the state's overdue debt is estimated at around EUR 10 million.
From an ethical and moral point of view, it is shameful that the government does not comply with the legislation in force.
To maintain the market, EUR 16-18 million a year would be needed".
This is the first Italian city that, in its concern over closures, has decided to remedy the problem in order to protect and boost single-room cinemas in both the city and downtown, through an agreement between the municipality and Anec.
The provisions would include tax incentives for operators and the benefits for the public to facilitate accessibility: viewers can drive into restricted zones and park at a reduced tariff in certain parking spaces.
"I like this initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities, even by introducing other measures, will follow Bologna's example.
However, it is also certain that traditional cinemas need to improve sound and image quality in order to be able to cope with multiplexes, because today's audience is much more demanding.
