Waves, sea currents, tidal tides, all renewable energy sources, which have been seen by giants like Chevron, who are now trying to get their hands on.
For a hundred years, they have been looking for ways to extract energy from the sea's movements.
Around 1980, when oil prices fell, the idea of using marine energy was put aside, but today the demand for environmental protection and the rise in oil prices are giving the sector a new impetus.
The World Energy Council in London (WEC) estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity demand could be covered by facilities for the use of waves of the seas.
This quantity is twice as much as what nuclear power plants are currently producing.
In addition, there would still be currents and tides.
The giants are on the move.
Enersis was the first company to commit to marine energy and signed an agreement in 2005 on a power plant to be set up in northern Portugal.
It seemed like a revolutionary move when the signature was announced.
Two years have passed since then, and more and more companies are opting for marine energy, including those who have been committed to traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying technologies that harness the energy of the oceans and is considering cooperation with us," said Wall Street Journal, a spokesman for an associate of the American oil giant.
The cooperation in question concerns the acquisition of a licence issued by the US Energy Commission for the launch of the Alaskan offshore energy project.
This is not of little importance, especially considering that the US is in the process of extracting oil in Alaska, and even President Bush has recently launched a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. in New York and Ocean Power in New Jersey are also on the road to extractable energy from the sea.
The technology is waiting to be developed.
According to experts, it is still primitive technology, even because the energy from the sea does not dispel doubts about the environmental impact.
Existing installations such as Portugal or Scotland are all small and therefore do not pose a major problem with the ecosystem.
However, in order to produce more energy on a larger scale, we need facilities with a more significant environmental impact.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses an interconnected buoy system.
The shocks generated by the waves and moving the buoys up and down are converted into hydraulic pressure by the pistons and cylinders placed in them.
The pressure's turning a turbine, and it's fueling a generator.
Electricity travels to the mainland on cables under the sea.
For now, there are four similar facilities at the design stage that are just waiting for a federal permit, and some of the energy produced would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started energy production for a shopping centre and a parking lot with the help of six submarine turbines located in the East River Strait in New York.
At tidal tides, the movement of water turns the blades of the turbines, and this rotating motion feeds the generator.
Verdant stated that it had a long list of partners who were just waiting for permits to use energy.
It's a tidal wave.
At present, the opportunities that can be exploited through tidal tides deserve special attention.
Although it is a temporary phenomenon, tidal tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and can therefore be considered a more reliable energy source.
New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as the other coastal states, spent 7.5 million dollars in 2008 to exploit the energy supplied by the tide, which is expected to rise to 35 million in 2009.
